Overview
Retail development is difficult to pull off economically. While retail is an important driver of local economic activity, sales productivity is highly sensitive to supply and demand dynamics and macro-economic forces that influence consumer spending.
Brick-and-mortar retail, specifically, is sensitive to rent increases and relies heavily on proximity to residential and office uses to provide customers. It is also facing ever-increasing competition from e-commerce.
Retail development is often hard to make economically feasible for a variety of reasons, including its inherent risk and costs pressures stemming from land values and a developer's need for leasing terms to cover construction and fit-out costs as well as potential vacancies. That often results in rents that small and independent retailers struggle to afford amid tight financing conditions and rising operating costs for the retailer.
At the same time, the rise of e-commerce and experiential formats has undercut demand for traditional storefront retail.
A threshold analysis is used to determine the minimum level of local demand (generally measured in terms of population, income, or spending power within a defined area) that will be necessary for a store type to produce enough sales to cover its costs and be economically viable.
